It is a duty to recover it.”
In all of Bolivia, a land without sea, people still vividly remember the lost coast to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, as well as the longing to sail the Pacific Ocean again.
Bolivia's hopes may be the greatest in decades, as the International Court of Justice is expected to rule on the case on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the impulse, a spirit of unity and calm and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
