John Edward: linguistic competences are fundamental for citizens of the world
The independent schools of Scotland have a long history of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in the exams that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students in all of Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS, for its English acronym), strive to deliver the best possible service to students and parents.
Independent schools have as their aim to prepare their pupils for further education, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy in the world.
As a sector of education that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages are still popular and desired in schools.
As Nelson Mandela said: "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, that goes to his head. If you talk to him in his language, that goes to his heart."
If you speak to him in his language, you reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and generate trust with people from other countries, you can't rely solely on English.
If we look at the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that the languages are at the top of the tables, with the pass rates being highest in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that make up the SCIS, showed that 72 % of students got an A in Mandarin, while 72 % of those studying German, 69 % of those studying French and 63 % of those studying Spanish also got an A.
This shows that independent Scottish schools support foreign languages because they are seen as a fundamental competitive advantage that children and young people will need in the future without a doubt.
Today, it is considered that languages are at the same level as the science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) subjects in the curriculum of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 revealed that, of the reasons given by employers on the difficulties they faced in filling jobs, 17 % were attributed to a shortage of linguistic skills.
Therefore, linguistic competences are becoming more and more indispensable for preparing young people for their future careers.
The opportunities for employment that require foreign languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to this competition, which will last their whole life.
The fact that you can communicate directly with people from foreign countries will give you an automatic advantage over your competitors.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, the 15%, was French.
This is why it is important to invest in teaching languages to children today.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be better equipped to find a good job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the United Kingdom in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools they can choose between several languages taught by specialist teachers.
The independent schools in Scotland devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children for life, whatever their future may hold.
It is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages still have a vital role to play for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages are "competencies for international communication".
The independent schools in Scotland will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
You have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
