North Korea says there is "no chance" of it disarming first if it does not have confidence
On Saturday, the Foreign Minister of North Korea informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and that there was no possibility of it renouncing its nuclear weapons unilaterally under those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly that North Korea had taken "important steps of goodwill" in the past year, including halting nuclear tests and missile launches, dismantling nuclear test sites and pledging not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we have not received any similar response from the United States,” he said.
“If we don't have confidence in the United States, we can't have confidence in our national security, and, in those circumstances, there is no possibility of unilateral disarmament.”
Although Ri repeated the familiar complaints of North Korea about the United States' refusal to accept a "phased" nuclear disarmament formula that rewards Pyongyang for taking steps, his statement is important, because he did not reject a unilateral nuclear disarmament without preconditions, as North Korea has done in the past.
Ri made reference to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump after the first summit between a US president in office and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June 2018, when Kim committed to working towards denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula and Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the Korean War of 1950-53, but the US has said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons before it can be considered to have ended the war.
Washington has resisted calls to soften international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on nuclear disarmament first and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its goal coercively, even putting objections to a declaration of termination of the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a fantasy of people who don’t know us.”
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.
Ri did not mention any plans for a second Trump-Kim summit, announced with great fanfare by the US president at the United Nations a few weeks ago.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, leader of South Korea, in the last five months, and added: “If South Korea had been the interested party in the denuclearization of the peninsula, the denuclearization of the peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Even so, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year's speech to the UN General Assembly, when he said that it was inevitable to direct North Korean missiles towards US soil after President Trump called Kim Jong-un "Rocket Man" on a mission to self-destruction.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in moving towards disarmament, but said there was still much to do and that sanctions would have to be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this: "We can take two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward North Korea for its advances.
However, as US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The sanctions of the Security Council must continue energetically and without non-compliance until we realize a fully verified and permanent denuclearization."
The Security Council has imposed sanctions unanimously on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut off funding for its missile and nuclear programs.
Pompeo chatted with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later said he would return to Pyongyang in a month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not good.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, but North Korea later denounced his "demands as those of a gangster".
In a meeting held this month, North Korea agreed to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the "appropriate measures."
He said Kim had told him that the "measures" he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Students at Harvard University learn how to get enough sleep
Thanks to a new course that is being taught this year at Harvard University, all students are now sleeping more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of all-night studying fuelled by caffeine.
A professor discovered that the students at the world's number one university are often unaware of basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, believed to be the first of its kind in the US.
His motivation for setting up the course came after giving a talk on how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked why she was just finding out about this now, in her last year.
He said that no one had ever spoken to him about the importance of dreams, which surprised me.
The course, which is being taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were sleeping only during the week.
The course lasts for an hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sporting performance and the importance of establishing a routine for going to bed.
In another section, participants are informed of how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
After that, an icon of the campus with interactive icons animates participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that it won’t change student behaviour immediately.”
However, we believe that they have a right to know, just as any has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco”, added the professor Czeisler.
He said that the culture of pride in "staying up all night" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and a good quality of sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, tiredness and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation makes the brain generate a feeling of hunger, so that it wants to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying biochemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after having attended one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the whole campus.
I hope that the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
The professor's recommendation is that students set an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by computer screens and LED lights, which can alter circadian rhythms, so that they would have problems falling asleep.
