The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new study, which has been carried out in a Scottish Highlands, is trying to discover how bats use the landscape to find food.
It is hoped that all that is discovered will shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help to guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and soprano pipistrelles, as well as the brown long-eared bat of Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in strategic locations on the property to monitor the activities of the bats during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations with portable detectors.
Experts will analyse the sounds picked up on the recordings to discover the frequency of calls by the bats and which species make them.
Then a report and a map of the habitat will be produced to create a detailed image of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser for NTS, is hoping the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
With this information, the benefits of habitat management can be determined, such as the creation of meadows and how forests should be managed to benefit bats and other associated species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
The turbines and the electrical cabling can also pose a risk to them, as well as insecticides and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
The bats are not really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes in achieving their goal.
They use a sophisticated technique of ecolocalization to locate ants and obstacles on their flight path.
The National Trust, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
It has ten experts trained in the subject, who carry out regular surveys, inspections of nests and, on occasion, rescues.
The charity has even opened the first and only reserve dedicated to bats in Scotland at Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is the home of eight of the ten species of bat in Scotland.
The director of the property, David Thompson, says it is the ideal place for them.
“Here, at Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats,” he said.
We have old buildings, many veteran trees and the right habitat.
However, there are still many things unknown about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us to understand better what they need to develop.
It is important to check for bats before carrying out maintenance work on properties, as it is possible to destroy a breeding colony accidentally, killing up to 400 females and their young, which would mean wiping out an entire local population.
Murine bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy their colonies.
The Scottish-born head of the Bat Conservation Trust has urged the public to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we know very little about how their populations evolve."
